# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hack-simmons
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:hack-simmons/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Arverne is located in Queens Community District 14 and its ZIP Code is 11692.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] It is patrolled by the New York City Police Department's 100th Precinct.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Vernam's original plan was to name the neighborhood Arverne-by-the-Sea.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] One grandiose plan, influenced by his wife Florence, included a canal running through the neighborhood, reminiscent of the Amstel canal in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] When this plan fell through, the canal right-of-way was converted into a thoroughfare, Amstel Boulevard, which, except for a stub west of Beach 71st Street, was later incorporated into Beach Channel Drive.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Located on the Rockaway Boardwalk, Arverne became well known as a beachfront community with inexpensive summer bungalows, hotels of varying expense and luxury, and amusements and boardwalk concessions.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] On January 3, 1914, a storm devastated the peninsula's neighborhoods and swept the 1,200-seat Arverne Pier Theater out to sea.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] On June 15, 1922, a fire leveled a large part of Arverne, leaving about 10,000 people homeless, although the neighborhood was quick to rebuild.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In 1928, a project to build 5,000 bungalows in Arverne was announced.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] During the 1950s and 1960s, the advent of commercial jet air travel encouraged people to travel to distant destinations during the summer, rather than to local beaches and resorts.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] As a result, many of Arverne's summer bungalows became vacant.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] New York City's urban renewal projects of the 1960s leveled most of the summer resorts and some of the residences, many of which had been abandoned.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In 1964, the New York City Planning Commission approved the designation of a 302-acre (122 ha) Arverne renewal area.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Two years later, the renewal area was expanded by 19 blocks.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In expectation of the upcoming urban renewal, vacant bungalows were demolished.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] However, the renewal project was delayed, and a grand jury was convened to find the causes of the delay.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] A gap in funding from the U.S. federal government contributed to pressures to cancel the redevelopment.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In 1970, the city announced it would develop 970 apartments in Arverne by 1972.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] By then, only about 100 of the original 900 bungalows remained.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Controversy later arose when the city decided to place 100 mobile homes instead of permanent housing for low-income Puerto Ricans.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] By 1973, Mayor John Lindsay was calling for 500 of 3,650 proposed housing units to be deleted from the Arverne redevelopment plan.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] As of yet, the 970 apartments in Arverne had not been developed.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] When the city re-opened Arverne to redevelopment in 1984, a 123-acre (50 ha) patch of Arverne only contained one structure: PS 106.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In 1988, the administration of mayor Ed Koch started asking private developers to build on the site.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The Dubos Point Wildlife Sanctuary was designated that year as part of the plans for redevelopment.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] By 1991, the plans called for the construction of 7,500 apartments over 10 years at a cost of $1.5 billion.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Finally, the late 1990s saw construction begin on a 322-unit development of two-family houses, the first such development in the 35-year-old Arverne renewal area.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The rest of the area's redevelopment was canceled after an economic downturn in the 1990s.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] People started dumping garbage in Dubos Point, to the consternation of residents.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In the early 2000s, Mayor Michael Bloomberg started to revitalize Arverne with new housing and parks.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] This built upon a movement started in 1999, when 40 houses were built in the portion of the Arverne renewal area between Beach 59th and 61st Streets.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] As of 2003, 97 acres (39 ha) of the "Edgemere Urban Renewal Area" was to have 400 houses built within it.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Of these, 47 acres (19 ha) would be houses, 35 acres (14 ha) would be a nature preserve, and 15 acres (6.1 ha) would be a segment of preserved dunes on the beach.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Arverne and other parts of the Rockaways increasingly got attention and press as the redevelopment of the beachfront continued.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] One of the largest developments, the 2,300-unit Arverne by the Sea, first opened to residents in 2006.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Despite an economic downturn in 2008, the $1 billion development was mostly successful, and units sold at prices of up to $1 million.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] By 2012, Arverne by the Sea was largely developed.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] New restaurants and retail establishments arrived as part of an effort to make shopping available to local residents at a hub near the Beach 67th Street station.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] Phase I was completed in 2011; Phase II was begun in 2006.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] In October 2018, construction began on the Tides development.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] By mid-2019, Arverne was undergoing gentrification as new businesses were opening in the area, which was still over 60% Black and 20% Hispanic/Latino.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] According to census data from the 2019 American Community Survey, the Black population declined as a percentage of the population to 56.8%.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The New York City Department of Education operates Arverne's public schools.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] These schools include PS/MS 42 Robert Vernam School and PS 183 Dr.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The Queens Public Library operates the Arverne branch at 312 Beach 54th Street.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The New York City Subway's Beach 67th Street and Beach 60th Street stations, served by the A train, are located in Arverne.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The Q22, Q52 SBS, QM15 and QM17 MTA Bus routes also serve the neighborhood.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The 8.6-acre (3.5 ha) Kohlreiter Square is located on the north side of Rockaway Freeway between Beach 67th and Beach 69th Streets.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] There are three wildlife sanctuaries in Arverne, all part of the Gateway National Recreation Area.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] The Dubos Point Wildlife Sanctuary is northeast of the intersection of Da Costa Avenue and Beach 65th Street, fronting Jamaica Bay.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] It was acquired in 1988 and named for microbiologist Dr.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] At the northwest corner of Arverne is Brant Point Wildlife Sanctuary, located west of Beach 72nd Street and north of Hillmeyer Avenue on Jamaica Bay.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] It was transferred to the jurisdiction of the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation in 1992.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] A third sanctuary, Vernam Barbadoes Preserve, is on Terrapeninsula, a peninsula between two inlets of Jamaica Bay west of Beach 75th Street and north of Amstel Boulevard.
[src:hack-simmons/arverne-queens] It was designated as the "Terrapeninsula Preserve" in 1997, but is commonly referred to as Vernam.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:hack-simmons/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:hack-simmons/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:hack-simmons/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell was born in Columbus, Ohio, in 1886.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] His father Patrick Purtell (born 1849), aka Pere Purtell, was an Irish immigrant who played professional baseball in the late 1860s and early 1870s and later worked as a foreman in a cracker bakery in Columbus.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] His mother Emma (born 1854) was an Ohio native.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell began playing professional baseball in 1904 at age 18 with the Columbus Senators and Decatur Commodores.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He spent the next three seasons from 1905 to 1907, playing for Decatur.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell made his major league debut in April 1908 with the Chicago White Sox.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He appeared in only 28 games with Chicago in 1908, compiling a .130 batting average.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He remained with the White Sox in 1909, appearing in 103 games and batting .258.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell had the best season of his career in 1910.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] On May 10, he became the first player in major league history to strike out twice in the same inning, suffering the indignity at the hands of Walter Johnson.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] On August 9, 1910, Purtell was traded by the Chicago White Sox with Frank Smith to the Boston Red Sox for Harry Lord and Amby McConnell.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] During the full 1910 season, Purtell appeared in 151 games, 143 as a third baseman.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He also led the American League in assists (320) and errors (49) by a third baseman in 1910.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell in 1910 also set a major league record for the fewest doubles (six) by a major league player appearing in 150 or more games.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He also ranked third in the league with 32 sacrifice hits.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He compiled a .210 batting average and collected 51 RBIs in 1910.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell remained with Boston in 1911, but appeared in only 27 games, 15 at third base, and compiled a .280 batting average.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell spent the 1912 and 1913 seasons playing for the Jersey City Skeeters in the International League.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] In 1914, Purtell returned to the major leagues with the Detroit Tigers.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He appeared in 28 games, 16 at third base, and compiled a .171 batting average.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] In 1918, he was the starting third baseman for the Toronto Maple Leafs.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] The 1918 Maple Leafs have been rated as one of the top fifty minor league teams of all time.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] The team compiled an 88–39 record, and Purtell hit .311 in 101 games.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] After retiring from baseball, Purtell worked as a grip in a motion picture studio in 1920, a bartender at a club in 1930, and later a landscape engineer.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] In the late 1950s, he moved to Bradenton, Florida.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] Purtell died in 1962 at age 76 at a rest home in Bradenton.
[src:hack-simmons/billy-purtell] He was buried at Mansion Memorial Park in Ellenton, Florida.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] Simmons was born in Brooklyn, New York, in 1885.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] Simmons began his professional baseball career playing in the minor leagues for the Montreal Royals in 1906, the Dayton Veterans in 1907, the New Haven Blues in 1908, and the Rochester Bronchos in 1909.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] In April 1910, Simmons had his debut in Major League Baseball with the Detroit Tigers.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He appeared in 42 games with the Tigers, 22 of them as a first baseman, and compiled a .227 batting average and .303 on-base percentage.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] On May 4, 1910, Simmons initiated a triple play when he caught a line drive off the bat of Billy Purtell, touched first base to double up the runner leading off, and threw to Donie Bush who was covering second base.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] After making his debut with the Tigers in 1910, Simmons returned to Rochester later that season and remained there through the 1911 season.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] In 1912, he played for the New York Highlanders (later renamed the Yankees).
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He appeared in 110 games for New York, 88 of those as a second baseman, and compiled a .239 batting average and .308 on-base percentage.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] Simmons returned again to Rochester for the 1913 season.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He then joined the Baltimore Terrapins of the Federal League.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He appeared in 153 games for the Terrapins in 1914 and 1915, 74 as a left fielder and 39 as a second baseman.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He compiled a .257 batting average and .331 on-base percentage in two seasons with the Terrapins.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He appeared in his last major league game on June 30, 1915, and was released by the Terrapins on July 11, 1915.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] In all four of his major league seasons, Simmons appeared in 305 games, 127 at second base, 88 in the outfield, 39 at first base, eight at third base, and six at shortstop.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He compiled a career batting average of .246 with 234 hits, 115 runs scored, 102 RBIs, 85 walks, 43 doubles, 28 stolen bases, nine triples, and two home runs.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] After retiring from professional baseball, Simmons continued to play semi-pro baseball in Brooklyn.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He was employed for nearly 25 years as a general inspector for the Brooklyn-Manhattan Transit system starting in 1917.
[src:hack-simmons/hack-simmons] He was involved in an automobile accident in early 1942 and died in April 1942 at age 57 in Arverne, Queens in New York.
